    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - VIBRATION DAMPER, CRANKSHAFT, MAIN BEARINGS, FLYWHEEL AND
        CRANKCASE - CRANKCASE (RECONDITIONING) - INSPECTION AND REPAIR
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="9">
        <title>INSPECTION AND REPAIR</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Threaded holes with damaged threads may be salvaged with the use of a "Heli-Coil repair".</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the crankcase deck for flatness using a straightedge and feeler gauge, use checking
                pattern (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150752">7.52</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ). If a 0.076 mm (0.003 in.) feeler gauge can pass, the crankcase must be replaced.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>DO NOT RESURFACE THE CRANKCASE. SURFACE DEFECTS BEYOND THOSE LISTED IN STEP ONE, ABOVE, ARE
                        NOT CORRECTABLE. REPLACE THE CRANKCASE.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Repairs for coolant and oil leaks in crankcase casting can be performed with certain
                restrictions as follows:
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">No repairs may be made within one inch of an internal rib, wall or boss casting. Repairs
                    are only allowed in the shaded areas shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150753">7.53</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Casting cracks cannot be repaired.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Leak to be repaired must be within tap drill diameter.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Maximum plug size allowed for repair is 1/4-18 NPTF.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Leaks to be plugged (repaired) must be at least 76.2 mm (3.0 in.) apart.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Locate the leak. Drill through using a 1/8-27 NPTF or 1/4-18 NPTF tap drill, depending
                    on size. Drill hole square with surface being repaired.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Tap 1/8-27 NPTF or 1/4-18 NPTF.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Do not over tap. Plug head must be above casting surface when installed.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Clean chips and dirt from internal passages.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Apply Loctite(r) No. 601 to the O.D. of the pipe plug; then install the plug.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Allow four (4) hours cure time.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Grind protruding portion of plug flush with casting surface, if desired.</para>
                <figure id="ef4150752" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12185" filename="../figcg1/cg12185.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.52. Crankcase Deck Flatness Checking Pattern</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150753" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg10236" filename="../figcg1/cg10236.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.53. Crankcase Casting Leak Repair Areas.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the lower cylinder sleeve pilot bore for erosion. If a possibility exists that water
                leakage may occur from erosion, the lower bore can be machined as follows:
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rework the crankcase as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150754">7.54</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Adhere to specified dimensions.
                </para>
                <table id="t4150706">
                    <tgroup cols="2">
                        <colspec colname="1" colwidth="60p"/>
                        <colspec colname="2" colwidth="372p"/>
                        <spanspec namest="1" nameend="2" spanname="s1t2"/>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">SYMBOL</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">DIMENSION</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>A (*) (***)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>4.954-4.956 in. (125.83-125.88 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>B</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>6.810-6.850 in. (172.97-173.99 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>C (*)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>4.9645-4.9655 in. (126.098-126.124 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>D (**) (***)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>4.818-4.820 in. (122.38-122.43 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>E</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>0.010 in. (0.25 mm) R. Max.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>F</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>0.175 in. (4.45 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>G</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>1.325 in. (33.66 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>H</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>7.965 in. (202.31 mm)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                                    <para>* - Diameter to be concentric within 0.03 mm (0.001 in.) total indicator
                                        reading.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                                    <para>** - Diameter to be concentric within 0.05 mm (0.002 in.) total indicator
                                        reading.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                                    <para>*** - Center line to be square with crankshaft bearing bores within 0.08 mm
                                        (0.003 in.) in 305 mm (12 in.).
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install a Lower Pilot Bore insert as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Obtain correct bore part number from the parts catalog.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Apply "Locoquic Primer Grade T" (aerosol) completely around the rebored area of the
                    block, and around the O.D. of the repair insert.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">When the primer is dry (approximately 30 seconds) apply "Loctite Bushing Mount" to the
                    O.D. of the repair insert.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>
                            <emph type="underscr">DO NOT</emph>
                            wipe off any primer since it is a catalyst that insures the proper curing of the bushing
                            mount. Curing time will vary from 30 minutes to four hours depending upon the temperature.
                            At 70&#176; F (21&#176; C) a one hour curing time should be expected.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Set the insert in the cylinder bore as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150755">7.55</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150754" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg5896" filename="../figcg5/cg5896.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.54. Crankcase Rework Illustration for Lower Cylinder Sleeve Insert.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150755" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14160" filename="../figcg1/cg14160.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.55. Inserting Insert Into Block.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Push the insert through the upper bore with the I.D. chamfer of the insert toward the
                    cylinder head deck.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the pilot and insert driver into the cylinder bore as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150756">7.56</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The machine shop should furnish the appropriate size drive, pilot and handle for this
                            procedure.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rest the insert, pilot and insert driver as a unit in position for insertion into the
                    lower bore. (Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150757">7.57</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .)
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the insert driver handle into the insert driver and pilot.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the centering plate over the insert driver assembly and into the counterbore as
                    shown.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Tap gently on the insert driver handle until the insert is located on the start of the
                    cylinder bore.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Drive the insert into place with a heavy hammer.</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect the piston oil jet tubes for blockage as follows: (Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150759">7.59</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Shine a light source under the small orifice in the tube end which protrudes into the
                    crankcase from its insertion point in the bearing saddle.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Position your eye to align with the large orifice of the piston cooling jet. If the
                    light source is visible, the jet tube is clear and requires no further service.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the light source is not visible, the piston cooling jet tube is blocked. Clean the
                    tube to remove any blockage.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150756" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14159" filename="../figcg1/cg14159.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.56. Pilot and Insert Driver.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150757" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14158" filename="../figcg1/cg14158.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.57. Installing Insert.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clean any piston oil jet tube blockage as follows: (Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150758">7.58</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .)
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Run an appropriately sized wire or torch tip cleaner through the tube orifice to remove
                    blockage.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Using filtered compressed air, blow loosened debris out from the jet tube orifice.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Reinspect piston cooling jet tube using a light source as previously described.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Do not remove piston cooling jet tubes unless they are damaged or cannot pass the visual
                            inspection after cleaning.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>ALWAYS WEAR SAFETY GLASSES WHEN USING COMPRESSED AIR.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the tubes are damaged or blockage cannot be removed, replace as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a pilot driver to remove the tube. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150760">7.60</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the new oil jet tubes using the same pilot driver.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Lubricate the oil jet tube O.D. prior to installing into the bearing saddle.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Recess the oil jet tube 1/8 in. below the bearing saddle. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150760">7.60</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>WHEN INSTALLED, THE OIL JET TUBE MUST NOT PROJECT ABOVE THE CRANKCASE BEARING SADDLE
                            SURFACE.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Refer to
                <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150604.xml" xrefid="hl4150604">"CYLINDER SLEEVE FITTING PROCEDURE"</hotlnk>
                for crankcase upper counterbore reconditioning procedures.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">For camshaft bushing service procedures, refer to
                <hotlnk document="e415_E41505.xml" xrefid="e41505">Rocker Arm Assembly, Camshaft, Tappets and Push
                    Rods".
                </hotlnk>
            </para>
            <figure id="ef4150758" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg10704" filename="../figcg1/cg10704.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 7.58. Clean Piston Oil Jet Tubes.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150759" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg12186" filename="../figcg1/cg12186.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 7.59. Inspect Piston Oil Jet Tubes.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150760" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11240" filename="../figcg1/cg11240.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 7.60. Piston Oil Jet Tube.</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
